This is `List.foldr f (List.get (xs ++ ys) 0) (xs ++ ys)`.
`List.get (xs ++ ys) 0` is the first element of `xs ++ ys`, which is the first element of `xs`. Let's call it `x₁`.
So left side is `List.foldr f x₁ (xs ++ ys)`.

Expanding `List.foldr f x₁ (xs ++ ys)`:
If `xs = [x₁, x₂, ..., xₙ]` and `ys = [y₁, y₂, ..., yₘ]`, then `xs ++ ys = [x₁, x₂, ..., xₙ, y₁, y₂, ..., yₘ]`.
`List.foldr f x₁ (xs ++ ys)` is `f x₁ (List.foldr f (List.get (x₂ :: ... [y₁, ...]) 0) (x₂ :: ... [y₁, ...]))`.
This is going to be `f x₁ (f x₂ (... f xₙ (f y₁ (... f yₘ x₁) ...)))`.

Wait, this is the right-fold of the entire list `xs ++ ys`.

The right side is `f (foldr1 f xs) (foldr1 f ys)`.
`foldr1 f xs` is the right-fold of `xs`. Let's say `xs = [x₁, x₂, ..., xₙ]`. This is `f x₁ (f x₂ (... f xₙ a) ...)` where `a` is the identity. In Lean, it's `List.foldr f (List.get xs 0) xs`. So `List.foldr f x₁ xs`. This expands to `f x₁ (List.foldr f (List.get (x₂ :: ... xs) 0) (x₂ :: ... xs))`. This is `f x₁ (f x₂ (... f xₙ a) ...)` where `a` is the initial value. Since we don't have `a`, it's actually the right-fold of the list elements starting from the first element.

Similarly, `foldr1 f ys` is `List.foldr f (List.get ys 0) ys`. This is `f y₁ (List.foldr f (List.get (y₂ :: ... ys) 0) (y₂ :: ... ys))`. This is `f y₁ (f y₂ (... f yₘ a) ...)`.

So the right side is `f (f x₁ (f x₂ (... f xₙ a) ...)) (f y₁ (f y₂ (... f yₘ a) ...))`.

This is getting very involved with the `a` (the identity element). But perhaps in the proof, these `a` terms get substituted or handled.

Let me try to approach the proof using the induction.

